title: For Sale:  STI Tactical 5.0 .45 with 5 mags and IWB holster
location: NW of Columbus 10 mins., Columbus, Ohio
postcontent:
Up for sale is my STI Tactical 5.0 .45. This is essentially a doublestack government 1911. You can see more at stiguns.com They are well known for making gun used in racing and competition but this is a variant intended for LEO and carry, etc. It has Dawson 3-dot Night Sights (~9 months old) with bull barrel and 3/4 rail. It has also been professionally hard chromed by Metaloy (it is not shiny/glossy chrome plating but more of a matte finish that is ultra hard for durability).
Included are 5 magazines, kydex IWB holster and kydex double mag pouch. This weapon is extremely accurate and have very low muzzle flip. The grip is the same angle and width as a standard 1911 and the upper half is, in fact, 1911A1 compliant. Weight is saved by employing a (changeable) polymer grip such that the loaded gun (12+1) weighs about the same as a railed bull barrel 1911 with 8+1. I have owned it for about 1.5~2 years and put about 400 rounds through it.
I can ship from FFL to FFL or do a FTF transaction after looking at your CCW ID. The gun, new, runs about $1900 plus $60 per mag and $85 for night sights, $75 for holster, etc.
I will also entertain trades plus cash for lower end stuff that I am interested in, such as a .308 Rem 700 SPS, a basic semi or pump hunting shotgun with exchangeable chokes, etc.. Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Palmetto State Armory M4 carbine profile AR15 w/ extras
location: North of QC's and West of Rockford, Quad Cities, Illinois
postcontent:
I have for sale a slightly used Palmetto State Armory AR 15 with a 16" 1:7 twist chrome lined barrel, carbine length gas system, and m4 feed ramps. This is the same rifle as the PSA 16" M4 Premium Carbine. It was purchased as a separate flat top upper assembly and a separate lower receiver and parts kit with all components being purchased brand new. I assembled it myself. The lower receiver is marked "multi" and can fire both 5.56 Nato and .223 Rem ammo. It comes with a Rock River Arms chrome bolt carrier group. This rifle has 200 rounds through it (170 rounds of .223 with 40 rounds being steel cased ammo, and 30 rounds of XM855 5.56x45 62 grain ammo.) without a single malfunction of any sort. It comes with 430 rounds of ammo (390 rounds of Federal XM855 5.56x45mm 62 grain FMJ ball ammo in the ammo can, 1 box of Winchester Ranger 60 grain .223, and 1 box of Herter's 55 grain steel cased .223) along with 6 magazines (3 steel magazines with gray magpul followers, 2 steel magazines with green followers, and one Gen2 PMAG). This rifle comes with an A2 rear sight with dual aperture for both close range and longer range shooting. The rifle will come in a US PeaceKeeper nylon zip case with 4 pouches for magazines and a zip-shut pocket for other necessities while you are at the range.

 There was a spot on the ejection port side (right side) where tool marks were left while installing the roll pin while assembling the trigger guard. The spot was touched up with an off brand (not birchwood casey) gun bluing by a buddy of mine....but it is still able to be seen. I've attempted to show the spot in the last picture. It could be touched up with some aluminum black for a better match with the rest of the finish. In no way does this compromise the safety or function of the firearm. Other than that, this rifle is in fantastic shape with very few other handling marks (one on the opposite side of the trigger guard, and one by the bolt catch from my ring). More pictures are available if you are interested.

 I have over $1,600 into this package. That said, I don't expect anybody to pay what I paid for it. $1,000 Cash only. $1,100 trade value (my original selling price). The only trades I would consider are a Ruger 10/22 model 1168 or 1102 in good shape, A Glock 19 with night sights, or a XDS in 9mm. All State and Federal laws apply (24 hour wait or 72 hours if a handgun is part of the trade, valid FOID card, record of transfer, etc). I am not looking to travel a great distance for this sale, but with that said I go to the IL QC's 5 days a week for work. Would also travel as far east as Rockford...possibly DeKalb if you are from a suburb where this firearm is legal to own. I would consider selling to an Iowa or Wisconsin resident if you are willing to cover half of the ffl costs. The only trades I would consider are a Ruger 10/22 model 1168 or 1102 in good shape, a "budget" 1911 in 9mm (i.e. $500 Rock Island Armory 1911 Tactical 9mm, Remington, Citadel....no Taurus) with a skeletonized trigger and hammer, or possibly a XDS in 9mm or 1911 in .22lr with the balance to be covered in cash. All State and Federal laws apply (24 hour wait or 72 hours if a handgun is part of the trade, valid FOID card, record of transfer, ffl transfer for non-residents, etc).

title: For Sale:  Self Defense/Shooting Insurance
postcontent:
If you use your Firearm in self defense, whether you actually kill someone or not, if you’re not inside your home at the time, you’re almost assuredly going to get arrested, go before a grand jury,and in some way incur legal fees.
Very few insurance companies are willing to provide any kind of insurance for using a firearm, even if it is justifiable self defense. Those who claim to provide such insurance may promise to cover you after a shooting, but the reality may not match the promise. After an extensive study of available policies across the U.S., we have found that these policies …
 •May not pay anything until after an expensive trial and you are found not guilty.
 •May have low limits on payments, sometimes as low as $5,000 total (which may barely cover a lawyer's retainer fee).
 •Offer no coverage for bail, so you may have to pay this yourself or spend considerable time in jail.
 •Offer no reimbursement for lost wages, so you may find it difficult to pay bills while you're in court defending yourself.
 •May be a rider on another expensive policy you are forced to buy before you get any coverage.
 •May have language in the fine print that prevents any support at all because the underwriter has no experience with the realities of firearms or criminal defense law

•Up to $250,000 Accidental Shooting Protection
 •Up to $50,000 Criminal Defense Reimbursement
 •Up to Unlimited Civil Suit Defense Protection
 •Up to $250,000 Civil Suit Damages Protection
National Deadly Force Association
http://ndfasd.wix.com/protection-plan

title: For Sale:  CZ 52 Pistol with holster & extra mag
postcontent:
CZ 52 Pistol in terrific shape with matching 3 digit serial.  Low use and kept well.  

The CZ 52 pistol is a roller-locked short recoil-operated, detachable box magazine-fed, single-action, semi-automatic pistol chambered for the 7.62×25mm Tokarev cartridge (the gun was originally designed for 9 mm Luger caliber but due to political pressures had to be redesigned for the Soviet then standard pistol cartridge). It weighs approximately two pounds unloaded. Military models feature either a parkerized finish or a gray oxide coating, while some CZ 52s were arsenal reblued in the 1970s. These re-finished guns are usually marked as such.
The CZ 52 has a deep (front-to-back) but slim (side-to-side) grip, as well as a low "hump" which meets the web of the hand at the rear of the grip. These ergonomics cause the barrel and slide to sit rather high above the grip, resulting in very strong felt recoil. The CZ 52 is also well known for its very sharp report and great amount of muzzle flash. Due to its muzzle energy, higher pressure FMJ ammunition fired from the CZ 52 pistol will penetrate even NIJ II rated ballistic vests,[4] or the PASGT helmet.[5]

title: For Sale:  Beretta M1935 .32 ACP
postcontent:
Cool old Beretta Automatic $275

In the early 1930s, the Italian army was impressed by the Walther PP pistol. Beretta did not want to lose a big Italian military contract and designed the compact M1934 for the Italian army, which accepted it in 1937. The M1935 is simply an M1934, modified to fire .32ACP ammunition.

The M1935 is a single-action semi-automatic blowback pistol that fires the .32 ACP ammunition. It is made out of carbon steel with plastic grips. It is fitted with a manual safety and when the last shot has been fired the slide is retained open by the empty magazine. The magazine capacity is 8 rounds. As this pistol was built for the Italian army, all parts were interchangeable, which simplified maintenance and manufacturing: a first at the time.

Cartridge	7.65×17mm Browning SR (.32 ACP)
Action	Blowback
Muzzle velocity	925 ft/s (282 m/s)
Feed system	8-round detachable box magazine
